									</div>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<div class="line-vert right"></div>

	<section>
		<div class="container border-container books">
			<div class="flex padding-x align-middle borders">
				<div class="cell small-18 medium-12">
					<h1>Colour Theory</h1>
					<p>
						The ongoing process of learning the effects of colour in context to each other, when mixing together to achieve a particluar hue or tone, and the visual and psychological implications of
						colour and form by great artists has always interested to me, including the example below.
					</p>
					<p>
						A friend introduced me to Scientific American magazine with <a target="_blank" class="underline" href="/Scientific-American-Pollock.pdf">an article</a> about a scientific study looking for
						repeating patterns in Jackson Pollock drip paintings. At first glance, it appears unlikely that something systematic could be found from the expressive physical act of randomly flinging paint
						off of a brush onto a canvas that he stood on. However, the computer analyzed study found that there was in fact repeating fractal patterning in his work, and that the means he took to arrive
						at that particular effect were deliberate.
					</p>
					<p class="text-sm">
						<em>* Fractals are infinitely complex patterns that are self-similar across different scales. They are created by repeating a simple process over and over in an ongoing feedback loop.</em>
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="cell small-18 medium-6" id="pollock">
					<a target="_blank" href="/Scientific-American-Pollock.pdf"><Image src={pollock} class="borders light" alt="Jackson Pollock article in Scientific American" /></a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<div class="line-vert left"></div>

	<section>
		<div class="container border-container films">
			<div class="flex padding-x align-middle borders">
				<div class="cell small-18 medium-9">
					<h1>Favourite Films</h1>
					<p>Coming soon.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="cell small-18 medium-9"></div>
